{{Infobox rockunit | name = Balder Formation | image = | caption = | type = [[Formation (stratigraphy)|Formation]] | age = [[Eocene]] | period = Paleogene | prilithology = [[Mudstone]], [[tuff]] | otherlithology = [[Sandstone]] | namedfor = | namedby = | region = Central and northern [[North Sea]], [[Faroe-Shetland Basin]] | country = | coordinates = | unitof = [[Moray Group]] | subunits = | underlies = [[Horda Formation]], [[Mousa Formation]] or [[Tay Formation]] | overlies = [[Sele Formation]] or [[Dornoch Formation]], [[Montrose Group]] | thickness = 30 - >300 m | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }} The '''Balder Formation''' is a [[Formation (geology)|geological formation]] of lowermost [[Eocene]] in age, found in the Central and Northern [[North Sea]] and [[Faroe-Shetland Basin]].<ref name="BGSLexicon">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=BALD |title=Balder Formation |last=[[British Geological Survey]] |series=The BGS Lexicon of Named Rock Units}}</ref> The formation is named after [[Baldr|Balder]], a god from [[Norse mythology]]. Layers of [[tuff]] are found, particularly at the base of the unit, deposited by airfall from volcanoes associated with the [[North Atlantic Igneous Province]].<ref name="Morton&Knox1990">{{Cite journal |last=Morton A.C. |last2=Knox R.W.O'B |title=Geochemistry of late Palaeocene and early Eocene tephras from the North Sea Basin |url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/content/jgs/147/3/425.full.pdf |journal=Journal of the Geological Society, London |volume=147 |issue=3 |pages=425–437 |doi=10.1144/gsjgs.147.3.0425}}</ref>
