'''Mare Frigoris''' (the "Sea of Cold") is a [[lunar mare]] in the far north of the [[Moon]]. It is located in the outer rings of the [[Procellarum basin]], just north of [[Mare Imbrium]], and stretches east to north of [[Mare Serenitatis]]. It is just north of the dark crater [[Plato (crater)|Plato]].

==Geology==
The basin material surrounding the mare is of the [[Lower Imbrian]] [[epoch (geology)|epoch]], while the eastern mare material is of the [[Upper Imbrian]] epoch, and the western mare material is of the [[Eratosthenian]] epoch.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}

==History==
One of the first images from a spacecraft of the sea were done by the [[Luna program]] of the 1950s and later NASA's [[Lunar Orbiter]] and [[Apollo program|Apollo]] missions of the 1960s and the 1970s.  In December 1992, [[Galileo spacecraft]] took a picturie during its flyby of the Moon through a violet filter.  It includes the surrounding features of [[J. Herschel (crater)|J. Herschel]], [[Pythagoras (crater)|Pythagoras]] and a few others.  It was featured in the Astronomy Picture of the Day (APOD) on July 31, 1996 titled A Violet Moon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apod.nasa.gov/apod/ap960731.html|title=A Violet Moon|publisher=Astronomy Picture of the Day (APOD)|date=July 31, 1996|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>

==Names==
Like most of the other maria on the Moon, Mare Frigoris was named by [[Giovanni Riccioli]], whose 1651 nomenclature system has become standardized.<ref>Ewen A. Whitaker, ''Mapping and Naming the Moon'' (Cambridge University Press, 1999), p.61.</ref> Previously, [[William Gilbert (astronomer)|William Gilbert]] had included it among the Insula Borealis ("Northern Island") in his map of ''c''.1600,<ref>Ewen A. Whitaker, ''Mapping and Naming the Moon'' (Cambridge University Press, 1999), p.15</ref> and [[Michael Van Langren]] had labelled it the Mare Astronomicum ("Sea of Astronomy") in his 1645 map.<ref>Ewen A. Whitaker, ''Mapping and Naming the Moon'' (Cambridge University Press, 1999), p.41, 198.</ref> [[Pierre Gassendi]] called it the Boreum Mare ('Northern Sea').<ref>Ewen A. Whitaker, ''Mapping and Naming the Moon'' (Cambridge University Press, 1999), p. 33.</ref>

==View==
[[Image:Mare Frigoris 4164 med.jpg|thumb|right|600px|[[Lunar Orbiter 4]] image of Mare Frigoris and vicinity.  This regional view is nearly orthogonal at top but highly oblique at bottom, and north is up and slightly to the right.  Mare Frigoris is the dark band extending from upper left to lower right.  [[Mare Imbrium]] and [[Sinus Iridum]] are in lower left.  Prominent craters include [[Plato (crater)|Plato]] with dark flat floor in bottom center, [[Harpalus (crater)|Harpalus]] near left edge within the mare, [[Philolaus (crater)|Philolaus]] at top center, and [[Aristoteles (crater)|Aristoteles]] in lower right within the mare.]]

==In popular culture==

This area of the Moon featured prominently in 'Behemoth', the second episode of the 1973 BBC science fiction mini-series ''[[Moonbase 3]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

