{{Infobox scientist | name = Piers Forster | birth_date = | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | workplaces = [[University of Leeds]] | alma_mater = [[University of Reading]] {{small| (Ph.D, 1994)}} | thesis_title = Measuring and modelling UV radiation | thesis_url = http://www.metnt.rdg.ac.uk/Scripts/Library/PHDTheses.asp | thesis_year = 1994 | doctoral_advisor = [[Keith Shine]] | awards = Royal Society Wolfson Merit Award {{small|(2011)}} }} '''Piers Forster''' is Professor of Physical Climate Change and Director of the Priestley International Centre for Climate at the [[University of Leeds]].<ref>[http://www.see.leeds.ac.uk/people/p.forster University of Leeds School of Earth and Environment]</ref> <ref>[http://climate.leeds.ac.uk/profiles/ University of Leeds]</ref> A physicist by training, his research focuses on quantifying the different human causes of climate change and the way the Earth responds. He is best known for his work on [[radiative forcing]], [[climate sensitivity]], [[contrails]] and [[Climate engineering|geoengineering]]. He has contributed heavily to the writing of [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] reports, including acting as a Lead Author for both the [[IPCC Fourth Assessment Report]]<ref>https://www.ipcc.ch/publications_and_data/ar4/wg1/en/ch2.html</ref> and [[IPCC Fifth Assessment Report]].<ref>http://www.climatechange2013.org/contributors/summary-for-policymakers</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brumfiel|first=Geoff|title=Cloud formation may be linked to cosmic rays|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=cloud-formation-may-be-linked-to-cosmic-rays|accessdate=26 November 2011|newspaper=Scientific American|date=25 August 2011}}</ref> and as co-author of the IPCC October 8, 2018 [[Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5ºC]].<ref name="IPCC_SR15_PolicyMakers">{{citation |series=Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5ºC: |quote="IPCC special report on the impacts of global warming of 1.5 °C above pre-industrial levels and related global greenhouse gas emission pathways, in the context of strengthening the global response to the threat of climate change, sustainable development, and efforts to eradicate poverty |title=Summary for Policymakers|publisher=[[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) |date=nd |access-date=October 8, 2018 |url=http://report.ipcc.ch/sr15/pdf/sr15_spm_final.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref><ref name="IPCC_2018_SR15">{{cite report |title=Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5ºC |publisher=[[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) |date=October 7, 2018 |access-date=October 7, 2018 |location=[[Incheon]], [[Republic of Korea]] |url=https://www.ipcc.ch/report/sr15/}}</ref>
== Career == Forster was educated at [[Imperial College London|Imperial College]], [[London]] where he gained a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in [[Physics]] in 1990. He was subsequently awarded a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Meteorology]] by the [[University of Reading]] in 1994. After research posts at the Universities of [[University of Reading|Reading]], [[University of Colorado|Colorado]] and [[University of Melbourne|Melbourne]] he was appointed a [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] at the [[University of Leeds]] in 2005. He has been [[Professor]] of Physical Climate Change at [[University of Leeds|Leeds]] since 2008.<ref>[http://www.see.leeds.ac.uk/people/p.forster University of Leeds, Professor Forster's home page]</ref><ref>[http://www.unitedbankofcarbon.com/about/piers_forster/ United Bank of Carbon, Biography]</ref>
Forster is principal investigator of the Integrated Assessment of Geoengineering Proposals project.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carrington|first=Damian|title=Reflecting sunlight into space has terrifying consequences, say scientists|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/nov/26/geoengineering-could-offer-solution-last-resort-climate-change|accessdate=12 June 2015|newspaper=Guardian|date=26 November 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.iagp.ac.uk</ref> He has doubts as to whether [[Climate engineering|geoengineering]] could be deployed effectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forster|first=Piers|title=Not enough time for geoengineering to work?|url=http://thebulletin.org/not-enough-time-geoengineering-work|accessdate=12 June 2015|newspaper=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|date=2 February 2015}}</ref> Forster is also trustee of a UK rainforest-protection charity [[United Bank of Carbon]].<ref>http://www.unitedbankofcarbon.com/</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Matthew|title=The tea room that planted 3M trees around the world to cosmic rays|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/ca00577c-c32b-11e4-9c27-00144feab7de.html|accessdate=12 June 2015|newspaper=Financial Times|date=13 March 2015}}</ref> He has a number of UK government and industry roles including being a member of the expert advisory panel for the [[Airports Commission]] <ref>http://www.gov.uk/government/groups/expert-advisory-panel</ref>
==Awards== 2011 [[Royal Society]] Wolfson Merit Award <ref>[http://royalsociety.org/news/2011/New-WRMAs-announced/ [[Royal Society]] Awards list]</ref>
