The '''Ruwenzori-Virunga montane moorlands''' is a [[montane grasslands and shrublands]] [[ecoregion]] of central [[Africa]].
[[Image:Ruwenpflanzen.jpg|thumb|300px|Lower Bigo Bog at 3400m in the [[Rwenzori Mountains]] with [[giant lobelia]] in foreground.]] [[Image:1172 ruwenzori.jpg|thumb|300px|View of the Rwenzori peaks, with giant groundsel plants ''([[Dendrosenecio]])'' in the foreground]]
==Setting== The ecoregion lies above 3000 meters elevation, and is divided into two areas: the [[Rwenzori Mountains]] on the border of [[Uganda]] and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], and the volcanic [[Virunga Mountains]] to the south, where the Democratic Republic of the Congo, [[Rwanda]], and Uganda meet. It is surrounded at lower elevations by the [[Albertine Rift montane forests]] ecoregion.<ref>Burgess, Neil, Jennifer D’Amico Hales, Emma Underwood (2004). ''Terrestrial Ecoregions of Africa and Madagascar: A Conservation Assessment''. Island Press, Washington DC.</ref>
The [[Afroalpine]] flora of the higher altitudes have much in common with the [[East African montane moorlands]] of [[Mount Kilimanjaro]], [[Mount Kenya]] and [[Mount Meru]].
==Flora and fauna== The ecoregion is home to a distinctive Afroalpine vegetation. Habitat types include lakes, marshy deltas and peat bogs, open montane grasslands, shrublands, enclaves of high elevation forest, snow fields, and glaciers. Giant [[rosette plant]]s, including various species of [[lobelia]]s and [[senecio]]s, are characteristic of the ecoregion. Vegetation varies with elevation, soils, and exposure.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
The upper montane forest of the [[Albertine Rift montane forests]], composed of cloud forests with ''[[Hagenia abyssinica]]'' and ''[[Hypericum revolutum]]'', or bamboo forests of ''[[Sinarundinaria alpina]]'', extends up to {{convert|3000|-|3300|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
Ericaceous forests form a transition zone between the montane forests and alpine moorlands, extending up to {{convert|3800|m|ft|abbr=on}}. ''[[Erica arborea]]'' is the dominant species.<ref name=Bussmann2006>{{cite journal |author=Bussmann, R. W. |year=2006 |title=Vegetation zonation and nomenclature of African Mountains - An overview |journal=Lyonia |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=41–66}}</ref> The ericaceous vegetation varies in growth habit, in places forming a dense forest of single-trunked trees, thickets of multi-trunked shrubs, or open shrubland reaching only 1 meter high. The ericaceous forest supports many [[epiphyte]]s.<ref>Wesche, Karsten; Georg Miehe, and Meinhard Kaeppeli (2000). "The Significance of Fire for Afroalpine Ericaceous Vegetation". ''Mountain Research and Development'' 20(4):340-347. 2000</ref>
Alpine grasslands and alpine shrublands extend up to {{convert|4500|m|ft|abbr=on}} altitude. Tussock grasslands include ''Festuca abyssinica'' and ''Carex runssoroensis''. The giant [[rosette plant]]s ''[[Lobelia wollastonii]]'' and ''[[Dendrosenecio johnstonii]]'' are found on both the Rwenzoris and the Virungas, while ''[[Lobelia stuhlmannii]]'' grows only on the Virungas.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
In the portion of the Rwenzoris above {{convert|4500|m|ft|abbr=on}} altitude, the alpine grasslands and shrublands yield to upper alpine dwarf scrub, also known as subnival shrub, where ''Helichrysum stuhlmanii'' forms isolated thickets.<ref name=Bussmann2006/>
The Virunga Mountains provide habitat for the endangered [[mountain gorilla]] ''(Gorilla beringei beringei)''.
